# Personal Jarvis — top-level runtime dependencies (Wave 6).
#
# Source of truth: this file. The committed `requirements.txt` is the
# hash-pinned, PLATFORM-UNIVERSAL lockfile generated from it with:
#   uv pip compile --universal --generate-hashes --python-version 3.11 \
#       --output-file=requirements.txt requirements.in
# Re-generate it after every bump. `--universal` is load-bearing: it emits
# per-OS environment markers (`; sys_platform == 'win32'`, `== 'linux'`, …)
# so ONE lockfile installs cleanly on Windows, macOS AND Linux — each OS pulls
# only the wheels that apply to it. A non-universal (single-OS) lockfile bakes
# one machine's platform wheels in and bricks `pip install --require-hashes`
# everywhere else.
#
# Versions mirror `pyproject.toml [project].dependencies`. Keep them in
# lockstep — a divergence between this file and pyproject.toml is a bug
# (enforced by scripts/ci/check_requirements_sync.py).
# `verify-wave6.sh` re-installs from the resulting `requirements.txt`
# with `pip install --require-hashes`, so unpinned/unhashed entries
# fail-closed.

